<article>
    <h1>6 VISIT A PET CAFE</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201223/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-23"><time>2020-12-23</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE LIVING WELL</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>A furry four-legged an­i­mal can be pow­er­ful in boost­ing your mood and en­hanc­ing your men­tal health.</p>
    <p>Stud­ies have found that pet­ting an an­i­mal for as lit­tle as 10 min­utes can in­crease the lev­els of the stress-re­duc­ing hor­mone oxy­tocin and de­crease the production of the stress hor­mone known as cor­ti­sol.</p>
    <p>Reg­u­lar play­ing with pets has also been shown to lower blood pres­sure and choles­terol.</p>
    <p>Dr Annabelle Chow, a clin­i­cal psy­chol­o­gist at Annabelle Psy­chol­ogy, said vis­it­ing a dog or cat cafe may be a good first step to re­lieve stress and fa­tigue.</p>
    <p>Non-pet own­ers can visit Cat Cafe Neko No Niwa in Boat Quay or a dog cafe in Bugis called We are the Fur­balls.</p>

